Third-party software
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ffmpeg / ffprobe (https://ffmpeg.org/)

    Footlight invokes `ffmpeg` and `ffprobe` as external subprocesses to do all
    cutting, cropping, scaling, and encoding. Footlight does not statically link
    or include their source code.

    ffmpeg and ffprobe are licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License
    (LGPL) version 2.1 or later, and — depending on which components are enabled
    at build time — portions may be licensed under the GNU General Public
    License (GPL). Their licensing terms are NOT the same as Footlight's.

    Any distribution that BUNDLES ffmpeg/ffprobe binaries with Footlight MUST:
      - bundle an LGPL-compatible ffmpeg build (avoid GPL-only components, e.g.
        do not enable `--enable-gpl` / `--enable-nonfree` configurations unless
        you intend to and can comply with GPL terms for the whole bundle), and
      - include ffmpeg's own LICENSE, COPYING, and notice files alongside the
        bundled binaries, and
      - comply with the LGPL's requirements for the bundled build.

    Installations that rely on a separately installed, system-provided ffmpeg
    (e.g. `brew install ffmpeg`) do not bundle it, and the above bundling
    obligations do not apply to that case. Footlight's own Apache-2.0 licensing
    is unaffected either way.

yt-dlp (https://github.com/yt-dlp/yt-dlp)

    Footlight can optionally invoke `yt-dlp` to download source videos. yt-dlp is
    released into the public domain under the Unlicense. It is an optional,
    user-installed dependency and is not required to render clips from local
    files.
